  "text": "We recently identified a gain of chromosome arm 3q as a recurrent chromosomal aberration that occurs at the transition from preinvasive to invasive, early-stage cervical carcinomas [CITATION_1] . We performed the present study to address the question whether gain of 3q is maintained when the tumors progress, and to identify additional chromosomal aberrations that might be required for further progression of cervical carcinomas. We now report the mapping of chromosomal gains and losses in 30 cases of advanced-stage cervical carcino mas. T he clinical data are summarized in Table 1 .",
